question.text: The molar volume of iron (56 g·mol -1 ) at 25°C is 6 cm 3 ·mol -1 . What is the density of iron at 25°C in g·cm -3 ?

explanation.concept_text: To solve this problem involving density , we need to use the density formula to calculate for the density of iron: ρ = density (g•mL -1 , g•cm -3 ), m = mass (g), V = volume (mL, cm 3 ) The molar volume of iron (6 cm 3 •mol -1 ) tells us that each mole of iron occupies 6 cm 3 . The molar mass of iron (56 g•mol -1 ) tells us that each mole of iron weighs 56 g. By dividing the molar mass of iron by the molar volume of iron, we can determine the density of iron: This is equivalent to 56/6. Therefore, the answer is A.

question.text: Which of the following samples has the greatest density?

options.label: A.
options.text: A mass of 100 g and a volume of 20 mL

options.label: B.
options.text: A mass of 50 g and a volume of 0.20 cm 3

options.label: C.
options.text: A mass of 2.5 kg and a volume of 0.20 L

options.label: D.
options.text: A mass of 3.3 kg and a volume of 0.05 L

options.label: E.
options.text: A mass of 0.10 kg and a volume of 0.30 cm 3

correct_answer_text: A mass of 0.10 kg and a volume of 0.30 cm 3

explanation.concept_text: To solve this problem involving density , we need to use the density formula to calculate for the density of each substance: ρ = density (g•mL -1 , g•cm -3 ), m = mass (g), V = volume (mL, cm 3 ) We also need to keep in mind that 1 cm 3 = 1 mL, so we can re-write all cm 3 into mL. Option A. A mass of 100 g and a volume of 20 mL Incorrect. The density of this option is (100 g)/(20 mL) = 5 g•mL -1 . Option B. A mass of 50 g and a volume of 0.20 cm 3 Incorrect. We can convert 0.20 cm 3 = 0.20 mL. The density of this option is (50 g)/(0.20 mL) = 250 g•mL -1 . Option C. A mass of 2.5 kg and a volume of 0.20 L Incorrect. We can convert 2.5 kg = 2,500 g and 0.20 L = 200 mL. The density of this option is (2,500 g)/(200 mL) = 12.5 g•mL -1 . Option D. A mass of 3.3 kg and a volume of 0.05 L Incorrect. We can convert 3.3 kg = 3,300 g and 0.05 L = 50 mL. The density of this option is (3,300 g)/(50 mL) = 66 g•mL -1 . Option E. A mass of 0.10 kg and a volume of 0.30 cm 3 Correct. We can convert 0.10 kg = 100 g and 0.30 cm 3 = 0.30 mL. The density of this option is (100 g)/(0.30 mL) = 333 g•mL -1 . As we can see, this sample has the greatest density. Therefore, the answer is E.
